1. What is Recursion?

Recursion is a technique where a function calls itself to solve smaller versions of the same problem until it reaches a base condition.

In this problem:
-> We reduce years by 1 in each call
-> Stop when years == 0

2. Time Complexity
-> Each function call reduces years by 1.
-> So the function runs once per year:

Time Complexity: O(n)
Where:
-> n = number of years

3. Space Complexity
Because of recursive function calls, stack memory is used.
Space Complexity: O(n)

4. Limitation of recursion
-> Uses extra memory (stack calls)
-> Slower for large inputs
-> Can cause stack overflow if years is very large

5. Optimization
-> Instead of recursion, we can use direct formula:

>   double result = initialValue * Math.pow(1 + growthRate, years);
Complexity:
Time: O(1)
Space: O(1)